== Configuration ==

This section gives an overview on where to configure various things in Paludis.

* [http://paludis.exherbo.org/configuration/bashrc.html toolchain and environmental package behavior]: '''/etc/paludis/bashrc'''
* [http://paludis.exherbo.org/configuration/keywords.html keywords] (allowing packages from unstable branch): '''/etc/paludis/keywords.conf''' or '''/etc/paludis/keywords.conf.d/*.conf'''
* [http://paludis.exherbo.org/configuration/use.html USE flags] (enabling package features): '''/etc/paludis/use.conf''' or '''/etc/paludis/use.conf.d/*.conf'''
* [http://paludis.exherbo.org/configuration/licenses.html licenses]: '''/etc/paludis/licenses.conf''' or '''/etc/paludis/licenses.conf.d/*.conf'''
* [http://paludis.exherbo.org/configuration/packagemask.html package (un)masks]: '''/etc/paludis/package_mask.conf''' or '''/etc/paludis/package_mask.conf.d/*.conf''' and '''/etc/paludis/package_unmask.conf''' or '''/etc/paludis/package_unmask.conf.d/*.conf''' respectively
* [http://paludis.exherbo.org/configuration/hooks.html hooks]: various subdirectories of '''/etc/paludis/hooks/'''
* [http://paludis.exherbo.org/configuration/output.html output and log behavior]: '''/etc/paludis/output.conf'''

== How do I...? ==

The [http://paludis.exherbo.org/faq/howdoi.html official documentation] already answers various of these questions, so this section just tries to extend it and be a little more basic.

=== Install a package ===

The most basic form is:
{{RootCmd|cave resolve -x net-p2p/retroshare}}

=== Uninstall a package ===

{{RootCmd|cave resolve -x \!net-p2p/retroshare}}

=== Update world ===

{{RootCmd|cave resolve -x -c world}}

If you want to review the changes that will be performed before they are actually applied, you can do this:
{{RootCmd|cave resolve -c --resume-file ~/resume.txt world}}

Now review the changes. If everything is ok, we apply these changes:
{{RootCmd|cave resume --resume-file ~/resume.txt}}

=== Install a repository ===

If you have configured unavailable layman repositories as per the [[Paludis/Guide#Repositories|the Paludis guide]], then you should be able to install (and uninstall) repositories just like regular packages.

{{RootCmd|cave resolve -x <repository-name>}}
If the repository name could be ambiguous with a package name, then you can tell cave explicitly that this is a repository:
{{RootCmd|cave resolve -x repository/<repository-name>}}

=== Sync all my repositories ===

{{RootCmd|cave sync}}

=== Tell the resolver how much work it should perform ===

There are 3 main switches that change the default behavior:
* <code>-z, --lazy</code>: Does as little work as possible, typically used when quickly installing a single package only
* <code>-c , --complete</code>: Does all optional work, typically used when updating 'world'
* <code>-e , --everything</code>: Does all optional work and always reinstalls, typically used when you want to rebuild everything after a major gcc upgrade for example

If you don't pass any of those switches, then the default behavior is roughly in between {{c|--lazy}} and {{c|--complete}}. These switches are in fact just shorthands for more fine-grained options. Check the manpage of {{c|cave-resolve}}.

=== Keep output logs ===

Add the following file:
{{FileBox|filename=/etc/paludis/output.conf|1=
always_keep_output_logs = true
}}

=== Make paludis quiet ===

Add the following file:
{{FileBox|filename=/etc/paludis/output.conf|1=
quiet = true
}}
